A 33-year-old man goes to his physician for a routine check of his health status. On physical examination he has the skin lesions seen here. These lesions have not increased in size since childhood. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis? <image 1> 

A. Keratoacanthomas
B. Seborrheic keratoses
C. Fibroepithelial polyps
D. Nevocellular nevi
E. Epidermal inclusion cysts

The image shows multiple small, raised skin lesions that appear to be benign and have not increased in size since childhood. Given these characteristics, the most likely diagnosis is:

D. Nevocellular nevi

Nevocellular nevi, commonly known as moles, are benign growths of melanocytes (pigment-producing cells) that can appear on the skin at any age but often develop during childhood or adolescence. They typically do not grow significantly over time and are usually harmless.
